{"type":"message","id":"00742b84","parentId":"cf00379a","timestamp":"2026-03-30T03:42:13.923Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"So there are 12 proposed orders (13 BUY/SELL lines minus the header = 13, but the file has 14 total lines - so 13 orders minus 1 header = 13 order lines). Wait, 14 lines total, 1 header = 13 orders.\n\nBut actually the guard report says 12 planned orders. Let me recount.\n\nActually 14 lines including header = 13 data rows. But the guard said 12. Let me check if some rows are filtered.\n\nActually looking at the guard summary: `planned_orders: 12`. So exactly 12 orders in the orders_df. \n\nThe count discrepancy is probably because the guard script filters the orders_df differently than my line count. Looking at the real issue though: the `NO_JOURNAL_WITH_PLANNED_ORDERS` RED alert means the script found planned orders but no journal entries, which triggered a halt for aggressive. The question is whether this is actually stricter than the other two approaches, or if it's just catching a real execution problem specific to that one day.\n\nThe rule itself isn't more restrictive—it's a universal check for data integrity. But the consequence is more severe for aggressive because it has more planned orders and tighter exposure limits, making zero journal entries more problematic. Meanwhile defensive and balanced each have one journal entry, so they're not triggering the same alert even though they might have similar order counts.\n\nI should trace back through the execution pipeline to see if there's a path difference for aggressive that would explain why it had no journal entries when the other strategies did.","thinkingSignature":"2888581d6059530ea8e16e280d115aa5535c92493a2507f99a7758dae89c2300"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_lsg0yymzetv6_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"cat /Users/ling/.openclaw/workspace/quant_projects/personal-a-share-research-system/research/reports/paper_aggressive_ex