{"type":"message","id":"d0ce7990","parentId":"4e119f99","timestamp":"2026-03-30T03:44:21.389Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I understand the full picture. The journal for 20260319 shows:\n\n1. On 20260319, the aggressive strategy bought 3 stocks:\n   - 002025.SZ (航天电器): 3000 shares at 59.0472\n   - 002151.SZ (北斗导航): 1900 shares at 45.4764\n   - 002173.SZ (创新医疗): 6000 shares at 29.6237\n\n2. Then immediately on the same day (20260319), all 3 were SOLD with `exit_type=rollback_corrected` and `exit_reason=盘中平仓止损（系统决定撤销早盘错误买入）`\n   \nThe position_count shows 0, nav is back to 996111.32, and the total return is -0.39%, but the account JSON is reporting cash: 0 while the journal shows all positions closed. There's a discrepancy between the account snapshot and what actually happened in the journal—the rollback corrected those erroneous buys on the same day, yet the account data isn't reflecting the cash being freed up. The aggressive account started with 1M, bought 3 stocks on 20260319 for roughly 474K total (59.0472×3000 + 45.4764×1900 + 29.6237×6000), then sold them all the same day via rollback correction, netting back to 996K with a -0.39% loss. The account_v1 JSON shows zero positions and 996K NAV, which makes sense. But I'm seeing something odd—the order plan from 20260327 shows a strategy_max_drawdown_pct of 24.52%, which doesn't align with the minimal drawdown shown in the journal. Let me trace back through the account history files to find where this 24.52% drawdown is actually coming from.","thinkingSignature":"b7306c6b7c904c397457354f945de91661c2358cae02b6b50dddcec7371567fc"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_dv8fujj7rjsn_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"for f in /Users/ling/.openclaw/workspace/quant_projects/personal-a-share-research-system/research/reports/paper_aggressive_account_v1_2026031*.json; do echo \"=== $f ===\"; python3 -c \"import json; d=json.load(open('$f')); print('nav:', d.get('nav'));