{"type":"message","id":"2cddee41","parentId":"1fb238f7","timestamp":"2026-03-30T03:54:30.451Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The fix is in place. Now let me also think about whether there are any side effects.\n\nThe fix:\n1. `resolve_pretrade_state` now returns `drawdown_pct` in the state dict\n2. `materialize_profile_signal_chain` now uses `state[\"drawdown_pct\"]` instead of `runtime_metrics[\"strategy_max_dd_pct\"]`\n\nThis means:- For paper trading, `--strategy-max-dd-pct` will now be the paper account's actual running drawdown (e.g., 0.39% for aggressive)- The halt check `strategy_max_drawdown_pct >= 10%` will correctly evaluate `0.39 >= 10` → False → no halt\n\n\n- Paper trading orders will no longer be blocked by the live system's 24.52% drawdown threshold\n\nBut I need to think through whether using the current day's running drawdown creates issues. Since we're resolving state before the trading day begins, the drawdown is calculated from the previous peak, which is the right baseline for risk management at that point in the day.\n\nThe key insight is that the halt check in `decide_mode` uses `max(combo_max_dd, current_day_drawdown)`, so even if today's positions haven't moved yet, the historical drawdown from the combo is what actually triggers the halt. For paper trading specifically, I should be checking against the paper account's own drawdown rather than the live system's, which is what my fix targets.\n\nNow I'm realizing there's another layer to this—the `prepare_paper_orders_v1.py` script generates orders for the paper account, but the halt condition in `decide_mode` is fundamentally designed for the live trading combo, not paper accounts. Paper trading has its own separate halt mechanism in the execution layer, so these are operating in different contexts. The `--strategy-max-dd-pct` parameter flowing through `apply_risk_to_merged_signals.py` is being used by the paper execution pipeline, but the halt logic itself was built for live trading decision-making.\n\nFor paper trading, the risk engine should absolutely rely on the paper account's own metrics rather than pulling from live system state. My fix handles this correctly. The paper execution config (`paper_live_trading_aggressive_v1.json`) does define its own `strategy_max_drawdown_riskoff_pct` threshold of 10%, which is what was triggering the block before—but this value shouldn't have been sourced from the live combo's drawdown in the first place.\n\nSince the paper account's actual drawdown is only 0.39%, the halt condition correctly evaluates to false now. Let me trace through the execution pipeline to see if the halt status propagates correctly to the paper trading logic.","thinkingSignature":"a3d2db1d071572820c68ba372c9409cb32c987f0c18896c90e019ea6b6bf4195"},{"type":"text","text":"修改完成。还需要检查一个地方——`paper_live_trading_aggressive_v1.json` 里 `strategy_max_drawdown_riskoff_pct: 10%` 这个阈值是否也在引用错误的回撤数据：\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_vlqcfx4qygu5_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"grep -n \"strategy_max_drawdown_riskoff_pct\\|strategy_max_drawdown\" /Users/ling/.openclaw/workspace/quant_projects/personal-a-share-research-system/scripts/apply_risk_to_merged_signals.py | head -20"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":63205,"output":682,"cacheRead":25020,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":88907,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774842853499,"responseId":"061926e5bcb755305bb450989ae5522a"}}
