{"type":"message","id":"c3ab28e2","parentId":"5d8860c3","timestamp":"2026-03-30T03:55:53.059Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I see! The key is in line 220:\n```python\nruntime.halt_reason = str(\n    authoritative.get(\"trading_status_reason\")\n    or authoritative.get(\"state_reason\")\n    or authoritative.get(\"halt_reason\")\n    or getattr(runtime, \"halt_reason\", \"\")\n    or \"\"\n)\n```\n\nThe `halt_reason` is taken from `authoritative.get(\"halt_reason\")`. Looking at `runtime_risk_state_latest.json`:\n```json\n\"base_runtime\": {\n    \"halt_reason\": \"strategy_max_drawdown_pct(24.5200) >= 10.0000\",\n    ...\n}\n```\n\nAnd `authoritative = runtime_truth if isinstance(runtime_truth, dict) and runtime_truth else runtime_latest`. So the halt_reason is coming from `runtime_truth` (which is `intraday_runtime.get(\"runtime_truth\")`) or `runtime_latest` (which is `runtime_metrics.get(\"runtime_latest\")`). Looking at the `runtime_risk_state_latest.json`, the `runtime_truth` field is present, which means the halt reason is being pulled from the authoritative runtime state.\n\nNow I need to trace through `run_live_execution_v1.py` to understand how `halt_new_buy` gets set. The function signature shows it accepts `halt_new_buy` as a parameter, so I'm checking where that parameter comes from and how it relates to the halt conditions I'm seeing in the data.","thinkingSignature":"d9559b3208a20451c9ffa28d8a07f9a561431ab3a2b1f6cfda1e99a9024429d5"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_pbfg2r4cy50s_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"grep -n \"halt_new_buy\\|hard_stop\" /Users/ling/.openclaw/workspace/quant_projects/personal-a-share-research-system/scripts/run_live_execution_v1.py | grep -v \"return\\|#\" | head -30"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":70508,"output":374,"cacheRead":25020,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":95902,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"c