{"type":"message","id":"06b7576e","parentId":"65ef62e6","timestamp":"2026-03-30T13:16:38.391Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Wait, let me think about this more carefully. The problem is that `journal_df.get(\"pnl_day\")` when there's a single row and it's a scalar, returns a numpy.float64. When there are multiple rows, it returns a Series. The issue is that `pd.to_numeric(scalar, errors='coerce')` on a numpy.float64 returns a scalar, but then `.fillna(0.0)` on a scalar doesn't work.\n\nActually, `pd.to_numeric(numpy.float64_value, errors='coerce')` returns a numpy.float64 scalar, and `scalar.fillna(0.0)` fails because float64 has no fillna method.\n\n\nSo I need to handle both cases - when it's a scalar value versus when it's already a Series. The fix is to wrap the result in `pd.Series()` first before attempting any Series methods, which will handle both scenarios uniformly.","thinkingSignature":"9dedc77ff0e4bd03077bee20df14a353b6330dc483a9433513c6fdab2ed8bbdc"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_h1wa0iip38t0_1","name":"edit","arguments":{"old_text":"    daily_ret_raw = journal_df.get(\"pnl_day\")\n    if daily_ret_raw is None or (isinstance(daily_ret_raw, (int, float)) and not pd.notna(daily_ret_raw)):\n        daily_ret = pd.Series([], dtype=float)\n    else:\n        daily_ret = pd.to_numeric(pd.Series([daily_ret_raw]).fillna(0.0), errors=\"coerce\").fillna(0.0)\n    nav = parse_float(account_payload.get(\"nav\"), 0.0)\n    if nav > 0 and len(daily_ret) > 0:","newText":"    daily_ret_raw = journal_df.get(\"pnl_day\")\n    if daily_ret_raw is None:\n        daily_ret = pd.Series([], dtype=float)\n    elif isinstance(daily_ret_raw, (int, float)):\n        daily_ret = pd.Series([daily_ret_raw])\n    else:\n        daily_ret = pd.to_numeric(daily_ret_raw, errors=\"coerce\").fillna(0.0)\n    nav = parse_float(account_payload.get(\"nav\"), 0.0)\n    if nav > 0 and len(daily_ret) > 0:","file":"/Users/ling/.openclaw/workspac