{"type":"message","id":"4c2b5aa7","parentId":"98fa5b8d","timestamp":"2026-03-30T13:49:57.822Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I see the prediction generation script is `train_ml_factors_all_a.py`. This script trains the model and generates predictions, saving to `ml_predictions.csv`.\n\nHowever, this is a full training script. For a daily update, we need to:\n1. Get new Qlib features for the latest dates (done - we refreshed the Qlib data)\n2. Run the model on the new data to generate predictions\n\nBut this would require running the full training script which is heavy. Let me check if there's a more lightweight prediction update script.\n\nActually, looking at the breadth_strict_oos situation - it uses `run_oos_from_existing_predictions.py` which reads from `ml_predictions.csv`. \n\nThe ml_predictions.csv has stopped updating because it needs fresh Qlib features combined with model inference. I need to understand how to run inference on new dates using the existing trained model without retraining everything. The scripts like `run_qlib_alpha55_live_signal.py` and `run_qlib_breadth_risk_tuning.py` might handle this—they load a trained model and run predictions on new Qlib data to generate fresh signals.\n\nLooking at the project structure, the Qlib data and predictions are in `/data/ml_dataset_full/ml_predictions.csv`, and the model artifacts should be in `/data/ml_models/` or similar. I should check what trained models are actually available.","thinkingSignature":"66749483edd5121cbbe461398abb02fd01c67f38f122e9092415c20f84fb96e0"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_phiy0xl2g2t4_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"find /Users/ling/.openclaw/workspace/quant_projects/personal-a-share-research-system/data -name \"*.pkl\" -o -name \"*.pickle\" -o -name \"*model*\" 2>/dev/null | grep -v __pycache__ | head -10"}},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_phiy0xl2g2t4_2","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"grep -n \"TODAY